children.text: There has not been a handrail fitted to the stairs/ramp in this area to protect the occupants from falls.
Part 3.9.2.4 Handrails of the NCC’s Building Code of Australia (BCA) requires that
‘Handrails to a stairway or ramp must;
be located along at least one side of the stairway flight or ramp;
be located along the full length of the stairway flight or ramp, except in the case where a handrail is associated with a barrier the handrail may terminate where the barrier terminates;
have the top surface of the handrail not less than 865 mm vertically above the nosings of the stair treads or the floor surface of the ramp (see Figure 3.9.2.4);
be continuous and have no obstruction on or above them that will tend to break a handhold, except for newel posts, ball type stanchions, or the like’ .
A handrail must be immediately installed to this area in accordance with the requirements of the BCA.
